    "content": "ğŸ§© Git Merge Methods Explained ğŸ”¸ 1. Fast-Forward Merge ğŸ“Œ What: Moves the branch pointer forward because thereâ€™s no divergent history.\nğŸ§ª Example: git checkout main git merge feature-branch\râœ… If main is behind feature-branch but has no new commits, Git just moves main forward â€” no merge commit is created.\nğŸ“Š Result: No extra commit. Clean history. Only possible when histories are linear (no parallel commits). ğŸ”¸ 2. Three-Way Merge (Default) ğŸ“Œ What: Used when branches diverged â€” Git creates a merge commit.\nğŸ§ª Example: git checkout main git merge feature-branch\rğŸ”„ If both main and feature-branch have new commits, Git creates a merge commit to tie them.\nğŸ“Š Result: Merge commit created. Retains full history of both branches. Good for preserving commit context. ğŸ”¸ 3. Squash Merge ğŸ“Œ What: Combines all commits from the feature branch into a single commit on the target branch.\nğŸ§ª Example: git checkout main git merge --squash feature-branch git commit -m \"Add feature X\"\rğŸ“ All feature-branch commits are flattened into one.\nğŸ“Š Result: Clean, single commit. Good for simplifying history. Loses detailed history of feature-branch. ğŸ”¸ 4. Rebase + Fast-Forward ğŸ“Œ What: Rewrites feature branch history onto base branch â€” keeps history linear and avoids merge commits.\nğŸ§ª Example: git checkout feature-branch git rebase main git checkout main git merge --ff-only feature-branch\rğŸ“ˆ Keeps history tidy and linear.\nğŸ“Š Result: No merge commits. Linear history. Can be risky if rebasing shared branches (changes commit hashes). ğŸ”¸ 5. No-Fast-Forward Merge (--no-ff) ğŸ“Œ What: Forces Git to always create a merge commit, even if a fast-forward is possible.\nğŸ§ª Example: git merge --no-ff feature-branch\rğŸ”— Use this to clearly show a branch was merged, even if no divergence.\nğŸ“Š Result: Always a merge commit. Good for clear separation of features in history. ğŸ” Summary Table Merge Method Merge Commit History Type Use Case Fast-Forward âŒ No Linear Simple updates Three-Way Merge âœ… Yes Diverged Default for complex merges Squash Merge âŒ One commit Simplified Clean history, single logical change Rebase + FF âŒ No Linear Clean history before merge No-FF âœ… Yes Always visible Always document a merge explicitly ğŸ§  Best Practices âœ… Use squash for feature branches in solo/team projects to simplify history. âœ… Use no-ff in protected/main branches for clear audit trails. âœ… Use rebase to clean up local commits before merging. ğŸ” Understanding git rebase ğŸ”¹ What is git rebase? git rebase is used to move or combine a sequence of commits to a new base commit. It is often used to maintain a cleaner, linear project history.\nUnlike merge, which creates a new commit, rebase re-applies commits on top of another branch.\nğŸ”¹ Syntax git rebase \u003cupstream-branch\u003e\rExample:\ngit checkout feature git rebase main\rThis reapplies your feature branch commits on top of the latest main.\nğŸ”¹ Common Use Case: Updating Feature Branch # Assume you're on feature branch git checkout feature/login git fetch origin git rebase origin/main\râœ… This puts your feature branch on top of the latest main, as if it was created from it.\nğŸ”¹ Resolving Conflicts During Rebase If conflicts occur:\n# After editing the file to fix conflicts git add \u003cresolved-file\u003e git rebase --continue\rTo skip the current commit:\ngit rebase --skip\rTo abort the rebase and return to the previous state:\ngit rebase --abort\rğŸ”„ Interactive Rebase Use this to edit, squash, or reword commits.\ngit rebase -i HEAD~3\rExample interactive menu:\npick 3f5e1f9 Added login form\rpick 89d2ac3 Fixed typo in login\rsquash d14e7a3 Updated form styles\rChange pick to:\nreword â€” change the commit message squash â€” combine commits into one edit â€” pause to change code during rebase ğŸ†š Rebase vs Merge Feature git merge git rebase History Keeps history with a merge commit Creates a linear history Commit Graph May look like a tree Looks like a straight line Use When You want to preserve all changes You want a clean history ğŸš« Donâ€™t Rebase Shared Branches âš ï¸ Avoid using git rebase on branches that others are working on (i.e., already pushed/shared), unless you coordinate with your team.\nğŸ”§ Example: Clean Up Before Merge Request git checkout feature/payment git rebase -i HEAD~5 # squash into a single commit\rThen:\ngit push -f origin feature/payment\rğŸ’¡ Tip: Use git log --oneline --graph before and after rebase to visualize the change.",
